``` The error "image alt attribute is missing" indicates that the `` tags in the provided HTML code are missing an `alt` attribute. The value of the `alt` attribute should be a concise and accurate description of the image. For example, if the image is a photo of a cat, the `alt` attribute should read "photo of a cat". updated_Description: The purpose of each link (or image button or image map hotspot) can be determined from the link text alone, or from the link text and its context (e.g., surrounding text, list item, previous heading, or table headers).Links with the same text that go to different locations are readily distinguishable.
prompts_baseline_two: You are operating on this website: https://www.alibaba.com/ Error: link-name Description: Ensures links have discernible text Suggested change: Links must have discernible text Incorrect: , , , , , , , , , , , , , , , , , , , , , , , , , , , , , ,
responses_baseline_two:
The issue with this website's accessibility is that it lacks descriptive link names, making it difficult for screen readers to provide context to the user. For example, "Home" and "Search" are not descriptive enough for a screen reader to understand what clicking on them will do.

To fix this, the website's links should have descriptive names that indicate what the link leads to. For example, "Homepage" and "Search Bar" would be more descriptive and easier to understand.

Additionally, the website's images should have alt tags that describe the image's content. This is important for users who are visually impaired and rely on screen readers to access content.

Finally, the website's CSS should be optimized to improve its accessibility. This includes using color contrast to make text more visible, using larger font sizes, and ensuring that the website's navigation is easy to use.

responses_baseline_two:
The given error message indicates that the website is missing the "title" tag. The title tag provides a brief overview of the website and is important for search engine optimization.

To fix this error, we will need to add the "title" tag to the website's HTML code. The title tag should be placed within the head section of the HTML document and should include relevant keywords that describe the website's content.

The updated HTML code will look like this:
```php
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
  <head>
    <title>Alibaba.com: The World of Chinese Business</title>
  </head>
  <body>
    <!-- Website content -->
  </body>
</html>
```
Once the "title" tag has been added to the website's HTML code, the search engines will be able to understand the website's purpose and display it in search results.

Description: Ensures the lang attribute of the <html> element has a valid value

updated_Description: The language of page content that is in a different language is identified using the lang attribute (e.g., <blockquote lang="es">).
prompts_baseline_two:
You are operating on this website: https://www.aliexpress.com/
        Error: html-lang-valid
        Description: Ensures the lang attribute of the <html> element has a valid value
        Suggested change: Lang attribute of the <html> element must have a valid value
        Incorrect: <html prefix="og: https://ogp.me/ns/website#" lang="de_DE">
responses_baseline_two:
You are correct. The html-lang-valid error is important to ensure that the website can be understood by screen readers and other assistive technologies. By including a valid value for the "lang" attribute, users with disabilities can better navigate and understand the website.

The recommended change is to ensure that the "lang" attribute of the <html> element has a valid value. This can be done by using a two-letter ISO code for the language as a value, such as "en" for English, "de" for German, or "es" for Spanish.

In the example you provided, the lang attribute is set to "de\_DE", which includes a prefix and additional information. This is not a recommended format, as the prefix is not necessary for the "lang" attribute to work correctly and additional information can create confusion.

Therefore, the corrected version of the code would be:
```
<html prefix="og: https://ogp.me/ns/website#" lang="de">
```
It is important to note that the language code used may change depending on the target audience and location of the website. It may also change over time as the website evolves and the language preferences of the users change.

The website you are providing me access to is <https://www.plex.tv/>, with the error being "aria-required-parent." This error suggests that certain elements of the website need to be contained within their respective parent elements, according to the ARIA (Accessible Rich Internet Applications) specification. The ARIA "required parent" rule ensures that elements with an ARIA role that require parent roles are properly contained by them.

To fix this issue, I would suggest that you review the website's code and ensure that the ARIA roles are being correctly used and that the required parent elements are properly containing them. It's possible that some ARIA roles are being applied directly to elements, which can lead to accessibility issues, so it's recommended that you follow the ARIA specification to apply roles to parent elements. Additionally, you should ensure that the elements that need to be contained by their parent elements are properly positioned and aligned within the HTML markup, so that they are easily accessible to users with disabilities.

responses_baseline_two: The listitem "Search" must be semantically used to denote a search feature on a website or application. It is not a semantic element that must be included in every website or application, but it is often used in e-commerce websites, social media websites, and search engines. It should be used in a way that is intuitive and clear to the user, and it should be easily accessible and visible on the website or application. The thought behind using the "search" element is that it should be used to provide users with a convenient way to find the information or content they are looking for.
